But you don&#39;t need to convert to a string. Assuming you don&#39;t want to or can&#39;t use `Integer.bitCount()`, then here is one way.
- initialize count to 0.
- check the least significant bit (LSB). If `n&amp;1` return `0` if LSB is `0`, else it returns `1`.
- `n&gt;&gt;1` shifts right 1 bit to expose next bit.
```
public static int countBits(int n) {
    int count = 0;
    while (n &gt; 0) {
       count += n&amp;1;
       n &gt;&gt;= 1;
    }
   return count;
}

